<Base title="Mammals&Suckers — Michalina Sablik">
  <div class="container page-content">
    <h1>Mammals&amp;Suckers</h1>
    <p class="exhibition-detail-venue">HOS Gallery, Warsaw | 2025</p>
    <div class="exhibition-detail-body">
      <p>A dialogue between two visual artists examining socio-ecological issues through critical sculptural engagement. The concept contrasts extractivist resource consumption with nurturing mammalian functions. The exhibition explores how "the act of nursing and sucking...is a fundamental life-sustaining function" while critiquing industrial extraction systems.</p>
      <p>The works reference philosopher Astrid Neimanis's interpretation of bodily fluids as metaphors for interconnected planetary water systems. "The Taste of Joy" features dozens of alabaster sculptures resembling both animal udders and gummy sweets. "Breaking Mercury" comprises latex tubes, wooden pipes, glass, and ceramic elements inspired by historical medical machinery and industrial milking devices.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="exhibition-detail-credits">
      <p><strong>Artists:</strong> Ida Karkoszka, Karolina Wysocka</p>
      <p><strong>Photography:</strong> Szymon Sokołowski</p>
    </div>
